Hi, great work on v4.3.0 — the fix for `.pick()` and `.omit()` throwing on refined schemas is exactly the right behavior.

I noticed that `.merge()` still silently drops `.refine()` callbacks from both operands. It looks like it was missed in the same pass.

## Minimal PoC

```typescript
import { z } from "zod/v4";

const A = z.object({ age: z.number() }).refine(d => d.age >= 18, { message: "Must be 18+" });
const B = z.object({ name: z.string() });

const Merged = A.merge(B);

// Refinement silently gone:
Merged.parse({ age: 5, name: "test" });
// => { age: 5, name: "test" }  — no error, .refine() was dropped
```

## Source

In `packages/zod/src/v4/core/util.ts` (line ~693), `merge` sets `checks: []` unconditionally:

```ts
export function merge(a, b) {
  const def = mergeDefs(a._zod.def, {
    ...
    checks: [], // silently drops all refines
  });
  return clone(a, def);
}
```

Compare to `pick`/`omit` which now throw:

```ts
if (hasChecks)
  throw new Error(".pick() cannot be used on object schemas containing refinements");
```

## Suggestion

Should `.merge()` throw the same error for consistency? The silent discard is surprising — a user calling `.merge()` gets back a schema that looks correct but has silently lost all refinements.

Happy to discuss or submit a PR if this seems right.

Best Regards,
YD

`z.string().cidrv6()` correctly validates IPv6 CIDRs at runtime using `new URL()`, but the `pattern` emitted by `z.toJSONSchema()` rejects many valid inputs.

**Affected version:** 4.4.3 (current main)

## What happens

```ts
import { z } from "zod";

// Runtime validation — correct
z.string().cidrv6().safeParse("2001:db8::/32").success;    // true
z.string().cidrv6().safeParse("2001:db8:1::/48").success;  // true

// JSON schema — incorrect pattern
z.toJSONSchema(z.string().cidrv6());
// {
//   "$schema": "...",
//   "type": "string",
//   "format": "cidrv6",
//   "pattern": "^(([0-9a-fA-F]{1,4}:){7}...|([0-9a-fA-F]{1,4})?::([0-9a-fA-F]{1,4}:?){0,6})\\/..."
// }
```

The exported `pattern` — `regexes.cidrv6` in `src/v4/core/regexes.ts` — only allows **0 or 1 groups before `::`** via `([0-9a-fA-F]{1,4})?::`. Valid CIDRs with 2+ groups before `::` are not matched:

| Input | Zod runtime | JSON schema `pattern` |
|-------|-------------|----------------------|
| `2001:db8::/32` | ✅ valid | ❌ no match |
| `2001:db8:1::/48` | ✅ valid | ❌ no match |
| `2001:0db8:85a3::/64` | ✅ valid | ❌ no match |
| `fe80::/10` | ✅ valid | ✅ matches |
| `::/0` | ✅ valid | ✅ matches |

`2001:db8::/32` is the canonical documentation prefix (RFC 3849) and appears in virtually every IPv6 tutorial and RFC example.

## Why it matters

The `pattern` field is consumed by OpenAPI validators, API gateways, and frontend validation libraries. Any system that applies the Zod-generated JSON schema directly will reject addresses that Zod itself accepts, silently breaking interoperability.

## Root cause

`$ZodCIDRv6` correctly overrides `inst._zod.check` to use `new URL()`, but `def.pattern` is still set to the incomplete `regexes.cidrv6` before calling `$ZodStringFormat.init()`. `$ZodCheckStringFormat.init()` then adds that pattern to `bag.patterns`, which `stringProcessor` in `json-schema-processors.ts` emits as the `pattern` field.

The runtime check and the schema metadata diverge at `src/v4/core/schemas.ts:885`:

```ts
def.pattern ??= regexes.cidrv6; // not used for validation
```

The comment acknowledges the disconnect but the pattern still leaks into the JSON schema output.

## Possible fixes

1. **Fix `regexes.cidrv6`** to correctly cover all compressed forms (similar to how `regexes.ipv6` enumerates eight alternatives).
2. **Don't set `def.pattern`** for `$ZodCIDRv6` at all, so no `pattern` is emitted in the JSON schema. Validators that need a regex would have to rely on `format: "cidrv6"`.

The results vary depending on the position of the “optional" in the schema with preprocess since v4.4.0.

```ts
// If “optional” is placed outside the preprocess block, `success = true`.
console.log(
  z.object({
    optionalNumber: z.preprocess(v => v, z.number()).optional()
  })
    .safeParse({})
    .success
); // true

// If “optional” is placed within the preprocess block, `success = false`.
console.log(
  z.object({
    optionalNumber: z.preprocess(v => v, z.number().optional())
  })
    .safeParse({})
    .success
); // false
```

The error message for the latter.
```
{
  "code": "invalid_type",
  "expected": "nonoptional",
  "path": [
    "optionalNumber"
  ],
  "message": "Invalid input: expected nonoptional, received undefined"
}
```

For version 4.3.6 or earlier, both will return `success = true`.

When using the `default()` functionality, zod appears to return a shallow-copy of the schema's default value. So, when the default value is a Map, or Set, etc. - operating on that default value later on makes for surprising results, because it means that the parser's output is no longer the same for the same input.

If this is desired, please add this caveat to the `default` documentation. Or, even better, allow the `default` function to return only `function` or primitive types. However, I find this to be a very surprising and incorrect result.

Min repro [Node 24]

```ts
import { z } from 'zod';

const itemParser = z.map(z.string(), z.number()).default(new Map());

type Item = { field: Map<string, number> | undefined };

const items: Item[] = [{ field: undefined }, { field: undefined }];

for (const item of items) {
  console.log(item);
  const itemsMap = itemParser.parse(item.field);
  console.log(itemsMap.size);
  itemsMap.set('HELLO', 1);
}
```

outputs

```
{ field: undefined }
0
{ field: undefined }
1
```

in core/utils.js, the following code triggers a unsafe-eval CSP error:

```js
export const allowsEval = cached(() => {
    try {
        const F = Function;
        new F("");
        return true;
    }
    catch (_) {
        return false;
    }
});
```

adding `z.config({ jitless: true });` doesnt solve the problem.

### System

zod v3.25.17

According to the source (and various articles) I can see that a transform callback receives a context object containing an `addIssue` method:

```ts
const schema = z.transform((value, ctx) => {
  if(isNotValid(value)) {
    ctx.addIssue({
      code: "invalid_element",
      message: "Not valid",
    });
  }
  return value;
});

schema.parse(someValue);
```

This work at runtime. However, in Typescript I get an error telling me `addIssue` doesn't exist.

Is this method deprecated? It certainly wasn't removed, and TS doesn't mark it as deprecated, but rather absent completely.

Confirmed in Zod v4.2.1 and v4.3.6 (presumably between as well).

-----

Resolution:

A. If the method is deprecated, the Typescript needs to be updated to indicate that it's deprecated, but not absent (until it is in fact removed).

B. If the method is *not* deprecated, it needs to be added to the Typescript definition.

